631
00:57:38,679 --> 00:57:41,080
He believed the Cartesian story.

632
00:57:41,080 --> 00:57:44,119
He was the last of the kind of Kantians.

633
00:57:44,119 --> 00:57:50,920
And he said that the first thing you have to realize is that we're in a here-now predicament, each of us.

634
00:57:50,920 --> 00:57:57,880
All we can ever really experience is what's happening here and now in our stream of consciousness.

635
00:58:00,520 --> 00:58:10,439
So the question is: how, given that we're this inner stream of nearness and now-ness, how do we ever get out into the world?

636
00:58:10,840 --> 00:58:14,599
It's that old external world story.

637
00:58:14,599 --> 00:58:19,639
And Heidegger's trying to say that there isn't any here-now predicament.

638
00:58:19,639 --> 00:58:28,559
That when you're Dasein coping in the world, remember that every here is all tied up with a yonder.

639
00:58:28,560 --> 00:58:30,080
That's what I'm leading up to.

640
00:58:30,080 --> 00:58:31,760
That's his next claim.

641
00:58:31,759 --> 00:58:41,599
Not only is the world all laid out in terms of near and far, thanks to us, but there is always a here and a yonder thanks to us.

642
00:58:41,599 --> 00:58:46,480
And that begins to get him both in the right direction and the wrong direction.

643
00:58:46,480 --> 00:58:57,920
He gets him in the right direction in that he's not thinking that we're just in a here-now predicament, that there's already a yonder and a future and a past in our experience.

644
00:58:57,920 --> 00:59:06,720
But it gets him into the trying to ask how we as individuals contribute the yonder as well as the here.

645
00:59:06,719 --> 00:59:09,359
And that's what he's going to go on about now.

646
00:59:10,319 --> 00:59:29,119
So we're going to, not only do we open a spatio-temporal shared world of equipment, which is what he should be talking about, but each of us opens, and this is we're not wrong, there's another phenomenon which he's more on to, which each of us opens his or her own spatial perspective.

647
00:59:29,119 --> 00:59:36,639
What he's really discovering is this complicated problem that we are in the world.

648
00:59:36,639 --> 00:59:38,800
We are being in the world.

649
00:59:38,799 --> 00:59:41,439
It's not that you're in your world and I'm in my world.

