665
01:01:12,119 --> 01:01:17,240
And that's because he wasn't trying to paint geometrical perspective.

666
01:01:17,239 --> 01:01:22,040
Heidegger knows that we don't have a geometrical point of view on the world.

667
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:29,080
That Descartes worked like that, Renaissance way of thinking about it, grew out of it.

668
01:01:29,639 --> 01:01:31,960
But we do somehow see the world.

669
01:01:31,960 --> 01:01:34,760
I see you from here and you see me from there.

670
01:01:34,759 --> 01:01:42,519
That's the sense in which we have, each of us have our openness on the world.

671
01:01:42,520 --> 01:01:45,719
And that's what he wants to try to get a grip on.

672
01:01:45,720 --> 01:01:48,679
It's so hard that he doesn't get much of a grip on it.

673
01:01:48,680 --> 01:02:02,960
But he wants to talk about the sense in which de-distancing is something that he not he wants to stay away.

674
01:02:02,960 --> 01:02:04,799
I mean, this is what he's getting at right now.

675
01:02:04,800 --> 01:02:09,599
He doesn't want to talk about de-distancing as bringing things close to me.

676
01:02:09,600 --> 01:02:11,199
That's the wrong thing.

