707
01:04:34,600 --> 01:04:40,359
And the more, that's, that is, they really matter to me.

708
01:04:40,359 --> 01:04:42,599
And so there's that kind of nearness.

709
01:04:42,600 --> 01:04:59,960
Then there's attention nearness, where Heidegger talks about how my glasses are, when they're on my nose and I'm not noticing them, are further from me than whatever it is, the picture I'm looking at in the museum, which is several feet away.

710
01:05:00,680 --> 01:05:13,559
So what he's trying to tell you is that existential distance is, or distance is the wrong word, nearness and farness is not measurable in terms of Cartesian distance.

711
01:05:13,559 --> 01:05:22,199
Because the same thing is going to be near and far depending on whether you're looking at it as available, accessible, mattering, attention.

712
01:05:22,199 --> 01:05:33,199
And then there's something else, the Merleau-Ponty issue about maximum grip, which he also sees, that when I've got a maximal hold on it for manipulation, that's when it's nearest.

713
01:05:33,199 --> 01:05:39,199
If it's right up against me and I can't get a grip on it because it's, I don't know, here, that doesn't have, that's not near.

714
01:05:39,199 --> 01:05:42,719
What's near is just when I can face it and hold on to it.

715
01:05:43,119 --> 01:05:45,119
That's another possibility.

716
01:05:45,119 --> 01:05:46,800
